const a = [
  {"id":3256,"text":"Which of the following is the obligatory and intermediate lipophilic and hydrophobic hormone in the biosynthesis of both estradiol and dihydrotestosterone?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1033.","responses":[{"text":"Testosterone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cholesterol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Progesterone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Estrogen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pregnenolone","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":3258,"text":"When is zona reticularis developed?","explanation":null,"reference":"Sadler TW. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 346.","responses":[{"text":"After birth","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"In ninth month of fetal life","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"In fifth month of fetal life","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"In third month of fetal life","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"In sixth month of fetal life","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3286,"text":"Diabetes insipidus is caused by deficiency of which hormone?","explanation":"Diabetes insipidus (DI) is a disorder characterized by excessive thirst and the production of large volumes of dilute urine. It is caused by the deficiency or inadequate action of **antidiuretic hormone (ADH)**, also known as vasopressin. ADH is produced by the hypothalamus and released by the posterior pituitary gland in response to low blood volume or increased plasma osmolality.\r\n\r\nThe primary function of ADH is to regulate water balance by increasing water reabsorption in the kidney's collecting ducts, leading to the concentration of urine and the preservation of body water. In diabetes insipidus, the lack of ADH leads to the failure of the kidneys to reabsorb water properly, resulting in the excretion of large volumes of dilute urine and causing dehydration and excessive thirst.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 938-939.","responses":[{"text":"Angiotensin II","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aldosterone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"FSH","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"ADH","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Insulin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11006,"text":"A patient who is taking antithyroid drugs for hyperthyroidism develops sore throat and fever. Her total leukocyte count is low. Which of the following drugs is she most likely taking?","explanation":null,"reference":"Davidson's principles and practice of medicine, 24th edition, pg. 644","responses":[{"text":"Nadolol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Methimazole","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Radioactive iodine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Propranolol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Digoxin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13837,"text":"A 60-year-old female presents to the clinic with complaints of pins and needles sensation along with burning feet over the last 8 to 9 months. She is a known case of diabetes and has been non-compliant with oral hypoglycemic therapy for the last 15 years. Clinical examination reveals sensory loss in a stocking pattern, absent ankle jerks, and subtle weakness of dorsiflexion of the toes. Which of the following is the dominant type of neuropathy in this patient?","explanation":null,"reference":"Davidson's principles and practice of medicine 23rd edition, pg. 758-759","responses":[{"text":"Amyotrophic neuropathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Entrapment neuropathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mononeuropathy multiplex","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Small fiber neuropathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Distal symmetric neuropathy","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":14252,"text":"A 34-year-old woman presents to the outpatient department for a check-up 1 year after she had been prescribed fenofibrate for a medical condition that causes deranged lipid profiles. She tells you that she often forgets to take her medication. \r\n\r\nFurthermore, she tells you that her maternal uncles have deranged lipid profiles for which they take medications. \r\n\r\nOn physical examination, her height is 5'4\" (163 cm), weight is 82 kg (180 pounds) and BMI is 31.6. She has bilateral yellow plaques on her eyelids and nodular, firm, painless swellings on the extensor surfaces of her hands. \r\n\r\nLaboratory studies are significant for triglycerides = 1100 mg/dL (12.43 mmol/L).\r\n\r\nWhich of the following conditions is this patient most likely at risk of developing?","explanation":"This is a classic case of familial hypertriglyceridemia.","reference":"Davidsons Principles and Practice of Medicine, 24th edition, page 638","responses":[{"text":"Pancreatitis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Coronary heart disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cholelithiasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Appendicitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatitis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15992,"text":"Which hormone functions as the second line of defence to prevent hypoglycemia?","explanation":"**Glucagon** is the hormone that acts as the second line of defense against hypoglycemia after decrease in insulin levels. It is secreted by the alpha cells of the pancreas when blood glucose levels fall, and it promotes the breakdown of glycogen to glucose in the liver (glycogenolysis) and the formation of glucose from non-carbohydrate sources (gluconeogenesis).\r\n\r\nEpinephrine is the second-line defense in counterregulatory response to hypoglycemia. Insulin, on the other hand, is a hormone that lowers blood glucose levels and decrease in insulin levels is often the first line of defense in hypoglycemia.","reference":"(1) Cryer PE. The barrier of hypoglycemia in diabetes. Diabetes. Published December 1, 2008. Accessed January 5, 2024. https://diabetesjournals.org/diabetes/article/57/12/3169/12810/The-Barrier-of-Hypoglycemia-in-Diabetes\r\n\r\n(2) Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 981, 983.","responses":[{"text":"Growth hormone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epinephrine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Insulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cortisol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucagon","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":18837,"text":"A patient comes into the outpatient department with severe pain in the epigastrium radiating to the back. After examination and investigation, a diagnosis of inflammation of the pancreas is made on the basis of increased levels of digestive enzymes from the exocrine part of the pancreas. Which of the following cells of the affected part of the gland are responsible for increased enzyme levels?","explanation":"In the case of pancreatitis, the cells responsible for the increased enzyme levels are the **serous acini**. The pancreas consists of both exocrine and endocrine components. The exocrine pancreas, which is responsible for the production and secretion of digestive enzymes, is made up primarily of serous acinar cells.\r\n\r\nThese serous acinar cells synthesize, store, and secrete a variety of digestive enzymes, including amylase, lipase, and proteases. In conditions like pancreatitis, these enzymes can become elevated in the bloodstream due to inflammation and injury to the pancreatic tissue, leading to premature activation of the enzymes within the pancreas itself, causing damage to the pancreatic tissue and the severe pain characteristic of the condition.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 815.","responses":[{"text":"Alpha cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Islet of Langerhans","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Delta cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Beta cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serous acini","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":18840,"text":"A newborn is brought into the emergency department with complaints of intolerance of oral feeding and greenish vomiting. Radiography shows duodenal obstruction with stomach dilation. Which of the following situations is most likely in the case mentioned above?","explanation":"**Annular pancreas** is a congenital condition in which a ring of pancreatic tissue encircles the duodenum, potentially leading to obstruction.\r\n\r\nThis anomaly occurs during embryonic development when the ventral pancreatic bud, instead of fusing with the dorsal bud in a normal manner, encircles the duodenum. This results in the formation of a ring of pancreatic tissue that can compress the duodenum, leading to symptoms of intestinal obstruction.\r\n\r\nPyloric stenosis is characterized by hypertrophy of the pyloric sphincter leading to gastric outlet obstruction, but this typically presents later in infancy and does not involve duodenal obstruction. Esophageal atresia would present with feeding difficulties and respiratory symptoms but would not typically show duodenal obstruction with stomach dilation. Hyperplasia of the pancreas and hiatal hernia are also unlikely to present with the described radiographic findings in a newborn.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 11th ed. Saunders/Elsevier; 2020; 215.","responses":[{"text":"Pyloric stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperplasia of pancreas","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hiatal hernia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Annular pancreas","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Esophageal atresia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":18843,"text":"A 32-year-old female presents with a history of palpitation, diarrhea, and weight loss for one month. Examination reveals bulging eyes that are exophthalmic in appearance. Blood tests reveal elevated levels of antibodies against the thyroid tissue, indicating Grave's disease. Which of the following features does the hyperactive follicle of the affected gland have?","explanation":"In Graves' disease, which is an autoimmune disorder characterized by hyperthyroidism, the hyperactive follicles of the affected thyroid gland typically exhibit **large follicular size**. Graves' disease leads to the stimulation of thyroid follicular cells, causing them to grow in size and produce an excessive amount of thyroid hormones.\r\n\r\nThese enlarged follicles are a response to the continuous stimulation by autoantibodies against the TSH receptor (Thyroid Stimulating Hormone receptor). These autoantibodies mimic the action of TSH, leading to increased synthesis and release of thyroid hormones. As a result, the follicular cells hypertrophy and the follicles expand.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 950.","responses":[{"text":"Large follicular size","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Acidophilic colloid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Large amount of colloid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Variable follicular size","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Basophilic colloid","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":18845,"text":"A patient comes into the clinic with a complaint of swelling in front of the neck. After examinations and investigations, a diagnosis of an enlarged thyroid gland was made. Which of the following does the enlarged gland develop from?","explanation":"The enlarged thyroid gland in the patient develops from the **endodermal cells of the primitive pharynx**. During embryonic development, the thyroid gland originates as a proliferation of endodermal cells at the midline of the floor of the primitive pharynx. This area is known as the foramen cecum, which marks the site of the future thyroid gland.\r\n\r\nThe thyroid gland begins as a small bud that grows downward in the neck, eventually detaching from the pharynx. As it descends, it forms a bilobed structure connected by an isthmus, becoming the thyroid gland. \r\n\r\nThe third and first pharyngeal pouches contribute to the formation of other structures in the neck (e.g., thymus, parathyroid glands); the dorsal bud is related to the development of the pancreas; and Rathke's pouch gives rise to the anterior pituitary gland.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 11th ed. Saunders/Elsevier; 2020: 168.","responses":[{"text":"Dorsal bud","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Third pharyngeal pouch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"First pharyngeal pouch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rathke's pouch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endodermal cells of primitive pharynx","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":18847,"text":"During the developmental process of the adrenal gland, which of the following would lead to the formation of chromaffin cells?","explanation":"Chromaffin cells of the adrenal gland are derived from **neural crest cells**. During embryonic development, the neural crest, a transient, multipotent, migratory cell population unique to vertebrates, gives rise to a diverse cell lineage, including the chromaffin cells of the adrenal medulla.\r\n\r\nThese cells migrate from the neural crest into the developing adrenal gland. In the medulla of the adrenal gland, chromaffin cells are responsible for the synthesis and secretion of catecholamines, such as epinephrine (adrenaline) and norepinephrine (noradrenaline), which are crucial for the body's 'fight or flight' response.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 11th ed. Saunders/Elsevier; 2020: 259.","responses":[{"text":"Notochord","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endoderm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coelomic mesothelium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Splanchnic mesoderm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neural crest cells","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":18851,"text":"Which of the following gives rise to the anterior part of the pituitary gland?","explanation":"The anterior part of the pituitary gland, also known as the adenohypophysis, arises from the **oral ectoderm**. During embryonic development, a structure called Rathke's pouch, which is derived from the ectodermal tissue at the roof of the developing mouth (oral ectoderm), gives rise to the anterior pituitary.\r\n\r\nRathke's pouch eventually loses its connection to the oral cavity and migrates upwards towards the brain, where it comes into close association with the infundibulum, a downward extension of the brain that forms the posterior pituitary gland (neurohypophysis). The cells of Rathke's pouch differentiate into the various cell types that constitute the anterior pituitary, each producing different hormones critical for various physiological processes.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 11th ed. Saunders/Elsevier; 2020: 397.","responses":[{"text":"Oral ectoderm","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mesoderm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neuroectoderm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oral endoderm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trophoblast","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":18856,"text":"How does the adrenal gland regulate blood pressure?","explanation":"The adrenal gland regulates blood pressure primarily through **aldosterone released by the zona glomerulosa**. The zona glomerulosa, the outermost layer of the adrenal cortex, synthesizes and secretes aldosterone, a mineralocorticoid hormone. \r\n\r\nAldosterone acts on the renal tubules, specifically the distal convoluted tubule and the collecting duct, to increase sodium reabsorption and potassium excretion. This sodium reabsorption leads to an increase in water reabsorption due to osmosis, which in turn increases blood volume and blood pressure. Aldosterone secretion is primarily regulated by the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system (RAAS) and serum potassium levels.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 358.","responses":[{"text":"Epinephrine released by medulla","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aldosterone released by zona glomerulosa","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Norepinephrine released by adrenal cortex","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cortisol which is released by zona fasciculata","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Testosterone released by zona reticularis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":18860,"text":"Which of the following most likely results in a decreased release of aldosterone?","explanation":"The condition most likely to result in a decreased release of aldosterone is **a rise in mean arterial blood pressure**. Aldosterone, a hormone produced by the adrenal cortex, plays a critical role in regulating sodium and potassium balance, as well as blood pressure. Its secretion is primarily regulated by the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system (RAAS).\r\n\r\nWhen the mean arterial blood pressure rises, it typically indicates an increase in blood volume and/or vascular resistance. In response to this increased blood pressure, the body attempts to lower the pressure to maintain homeostasis. One way it does this is by reducing the secretion of aldosterone. Lower levels of aldosterone lead to decreased sodium reabsorption (and consequent water reabsorption) in the kidneys, resulting in increased urinary excretion of sodium and water, which in turn helps to reduce blood volume and pressure.\r\n\r\nDecreased Na+ concentration at the macula densa, a fall in mean arterial blood pressure, a rise in serum potassium, and an increase in renin secretion by the kidney would all typically stimulate aldosterone secretion to counteract these changes.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 358.","responses":[{"text":"Decreased Na+ concentration at macula densa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A rise in serum potassium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A rise in mean arterial blood pressure","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"An increase in renin secretion by kidney","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A fall in mean arterial blood pressure","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":18872,"text":"A 40-year-old man complains of chronic fatigue, aching muscles, and occasional numbness in his fingers. Physical examination reveals a modest weight gain but no goiter is detected. Laboratory findings include TSH \u003e10 uU/L (normal range, 0.5 to 5 uU/L); free T4, low to low-normal. Which of the following are these findings most consistent with?","explanation":"The patient's symptoms and laboratory findings are most consistent with **hypothyroidism as a result of autoimmune thyroid disease**. The key indicators here are the elevated TSH level (\u003e10 uU/L) and the low to low-normal free T4 level. \r\n\r\nIn primary hypothyroidism, the thyroid gland is underactive, resulting in decreased production of thyroid hormones, such as thyroxine (T4). The low level of thyroid hormone leads to an increased secretion of TSH (thyroid-stimulating hormone) by the pituitary gland, as the body attempts to stimulate the thyroid to produce more hormone. This feedback mechanism results in the elevated TSH levels observed in the patient.\r\n\r\nAutoimmune thyroid disease, such as Hashimoto's thyroiditis, is a common cause of hypothyroidism. In this condition, the immune system mistakenly attacks the thyroid gland, impairing its ability to produce hormones. The patient's symptoms of chronic fatigue, aching muscles, and occasional numbness, along with modest weight gain, are typical of hypothyroidism.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 951.","responses":[{"text":"Hyperthyroidism as a result of autoimmune thyroid disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypothyroidism as a result of autoimmune thyroid disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypothyroidism as a result of iodine deficiency","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperthyroidism secondary to a hypothalamic-pituitary defect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypothyroidism secondary to a hypothalamic-pituitary defect","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":18949,"text":"Which of the following is consistent with a decreased rate of ACTH secretion?","explanation":"A decreased rate of ACTH (adrenocorticotropic hormone) secretion is most consistent with **long-term use of glucocorticoids**. Glucocorticoids, like cortisol, are part of the body's stress response and are regulated by the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal (HPA) axis. When glucocorticoids are taken exogenously, as in long-term medication use, they exert a negative feedback effect on the pituitary gland and hypothalamus.\r\n\r\nThis feedback inhibits the secretion of corticotropin-releasing hormone (CRH) from the hypothalamus and ACTH from the pituitary gland. As a result, the body's own production of glucocorticoids (from the adrenal cortex) decreases due to reduced stimulation by ACTH. This phenomenon is a well-known complication of prolonged steroid therapy and can lead to adrenal insufficiency if the exogenous steroids are abruptly discontinued.\r\n\r\nA pituitary adenoma, especially an ACTH-secreting one, would increase ACTH production. Stress due to emotional trauma typically activates the HPA axis, increasing ACTH secretion. Low serum glucocorticoid levels would normally stimulate ACTH production as part of the body's feedback mechanism. Primary adrenal insufficiency (Addison's disease) leads to increased ACTH levels due to loss of negative feedback from reduced adrenal glucocorticoid production.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 970.","responses":[{"text":"Stress as a result of emotional trauma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pituitary adenoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Long-term use of glucocorticoids","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Low serum glucocorticoid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Primary adrenal insufficiency","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":18952,"text":"As part of a routine clinical examination, a patient’s serum electrolyte levels were measured. Among the measurements, it was determined that the total plasma calcium concentration was 10.2 mg/dL. What percentage of total plasma calcium is normally present as the free active Ca+ ion?","explanation":"Normally, about **50%** of total plasma calcium is present as the free active Ca²⁺ ion. In blood plasma, calcium exists in three forms: free (ionized), bound to proteins (primarily albumin), and complexed with anions such as phosphate and citrate. \r\n\r\nThe ionized form of calcium is the physiologically active form, playing crucial roles in various physiological processes including muscle contraction, nerve conduction, and blood coagulation. It's tightly regulated by the body and is the form most directly influenced by hormones like parathyroid hormone (PTH) and calcitriol (active vitamin D).\r\n\r\nThe remaining 50% of the total plasma calcium is either bound to proteins (about 40%) or complexed with anions (about 10%). The protein-bound and complexed calcium is physiologically inactive but serves as a reservoir that can be tapped into to maintain the level of ionized calcium within a narrow and optimal range.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 991.","responses":[{"text":"50%","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"25%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"100%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"60%","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":18953,"text":"A 30-year-old woman completed a routine pregnancy with the uncomplicated delivery of a normal-sized baby girl 6 months ago. The woman is currently experiencing galactorrhea (persistent discharge of milk-like secretions from the breast) and has not yet resumed regular menstrual periods. The baby had been bottle-fed since birth. What is the most likely explanation of the galactorrhea?","explanation":"Galactorrhea, the persistent and inappropriate discharge of milk-like secretions from the breast, is often associated with hyperprolactinemia, or **elevated levels of prolactin.** Prolactin is a hormone produced by the anterior pituitary gland, primarily responsible for initiating and maintaining lactation.\r\n\r\nIn this case, the woman has not resumed her regular menstrual periods, which can be a consequence of elevated prolactin levels. High prolactin can suppress the secretion of gonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH), leading to reduced levels of follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) and luteinizing hormone (LH), and thus affecting the menstrual cycle. \r\n\r\nThe fact that the baby has been bottle-fed since birth is also relevant. Breastfeeding can lead to sustained high levels of prolactin due to nipple stimulation, but this is not the case here. The absence of breastfeeding should normally lead to a decrease in prolactin levels and the cessation of lactation.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1058.","responses":[{"text":"Excess prolactin secretion","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Normal postpartum response","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased dopamine synthesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Insufficient TSH secretion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reduced growth hormone secretion","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":18956,"text":"Which of the following hormonal treatments would provide the greatest therapeutic benefit in patients with acromegaly?","explanation":"Acromegaly is a disorder characterized by the excessive production of growth hormone (GH) from the anterior pituitary gland, often due to a benign tumor called a pituitary adenoma. This excess GH leads to the overproduction of insulin-like growth factor 1 (IGF-1) and results in the abnormal growth of tissues and organs, causing characteristic features such as enlarged hands, feet, and facial features.\r\n\r\n**Somatostatin** is a hormone that plays a crucial role in regulating the release of GH. It acts as an inhibitor of GH secretion. Therefore, using somatostatin analogs like octreotide or lanreotide in the treatment of acromegaly can effectively suppress GH release from the pituitary tumor. This leads to a reduction in the symptoms and complications associated with acromegaly and can help normalize IGF-1 levels.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 932.","responses":[{"text":"Somatostatin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"GHRH","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucocorticoid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Growth hormone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Insulin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":18958,"text":"Which of the following receptors are responsible for mediating the lipolytic effect of catecholamines?","explanation":"The lipolytic effect of catecholamines is actually mediated primarily by **β1 adrenergic receptors**. These receptors, when stimulated by catecholamines such as epinephrine and norepinephrine, enhance the breakdown of triglycerides into free fatty acids and glycerol in adipose tissue, a process known as lipolysis.\r\n\r\nThe activation of β1 adrenergic receptors in adipose tissue leads to an increase in cyclic AMP (cAMP) levels. This occurs through the stimulation of adenylate cyclase, which converts ATP to cAMP. Increased cAMP then activates protein kinase A (PKA), which in turn phosphorylates hormone-sensitive lipase, the enzyme responsible for catalyzing the breakdown of stored triglycerides.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 768.","responses":[{"text":"β1 adrenergic receptors","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"β3 adrenergic receptors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"α2 adrenergic receptors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"α1 adrenergic receptors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"β2 adrenergic receptors","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":18961,"text":"Which of the following transporters does glucose use to enter the pancreatic beta cells in response to hypoglycemia?","explanation":"The transporter responsible for glucose entry into pancreatic beta cells, especially in response to low glucose levels, is **GLUT-2**.\r\n\r\nGLUT-2 is a glucose transporter found in several tissues, including the pancreas. It plays a critical role in glucose sensing by beta cells. When blood glucose levels are low, GLUT-2 allows glucose to enter the beta cells. As glucose enters, it undergoes metabolism, leading to the generation of ATP (adenosine triphosphate). This rise in ATP levels within the beta cells triggers the release of insulin into the bloodstream.\r\n\r\nGLUT-2 is unique among glucose transporters because it has a high Km (Michaelis-Menten constant) value, meaning it has a lower affinity for glucose compared to other GLUT transporters like GLUT-4. This lower affinity allows it to efficiently transport glucose even when blood glucose levels are relatively low, ensuring that beta cells can sense and respond to hypoglycemia appropriately.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 979.","responses":[{"text":"GLUT-4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"GLUT-3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"GLUT-5","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"GLUT-1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"GLUT-2","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":18962,"text":"The emergency room receives a 2-month-old boy with worsening \"floppiness\" and poor eating. The baby was born vaginally to a 38-year-old lady. The parents call the baby a \"good baby\" who rarely cries and sleeps through the night but has been hard to wake for breastfeeding. Stools are now tiny and pellet-like. Examination reveals a hypotonic child with a big tongue, anterior fontanelle, and reducible umbilical hernia. Which of the following conditions is the infant suffering from?","explanation":"These clinical findings are highly suggestive of **hypothyroidism** in a newborn, specifically a condition known as congenital hypothyroidism.\r\n\r\nCongenital hypothyroidism occurs when the thyroid gland does not produce an adequate amount of thyroid hormones from birth. This condition can lead to various developmental issues, including poor muscle tone (hypotonia), developmental delay, and characteristic physical features like a large tongue and umbilical hernia.\r\n\r\nThe \"good baby\" behavior, with infrequent crying and excessive sleepiness, can be attributed to the effects of hypothyroidism on the infant's overall metabolism and energy levels.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 953.","responses":[{"text":"Down syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Addison's disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypothyroidism","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Botulism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Galactosemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":18963,"text":"A postpartum 24-year-old with gestational diabetes requests a follow-up. Diet alone controls her blood glucose 12 weeks after giving birth. Her fasting glucose is 100-120 mg/dL. Her medical history is otherwise normal. Vitals, BMI, and physical exam are normal. Her gestational diabetes and fasting hyperglycemia are likely genetic. Which enzyme's reduced activity is likely responsible?","explanation":"**Glucokinase** plays a crucial role in the regulation of blood glucose levels by facilitating the phosphorylation of glucose in the liver and pancreatic beta cells. In the liver, it helps trap glucose by converting it into glucose-6-phosphate, which can be further metabolized or stored as glycogen. In pancreatic beta cells, it serves as a glucose sensor, initiating insulin release when blood glucose levels rise.\r\n\r\nIn cases where there is a genetic defect or reduced activity of glucokinase, as may be the situation here, it can lead to impaired glucose uptake and utilization. This results in elevated fasting blood glucose levels, a hallmark of conditions like maturity-onset diabetes of the young (MODY), which often have a genetic basis.\r\n\r\nTherefore, it is likely that reduced activity of **glucokinase** is responsible for the persistent fasting hyperglycemia observed in this patient, contributing to her gestational diabetes and ongoing glucose control challenges postpartum.","reference":"(1) Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 845.\r\n\r\n(2) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1099.","responses":[{"text":"Lactate dehydrogenase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Enolase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucokinase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Phosphofructokinase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pyruvate kinase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":18966,"text":"Increase in which of the following actions of catecholamine on the cardiovascular system is mediated by alpha receptors only?","explanation":"The action of catecholamines on the cardiovascular system that is mediated specifically by alpha receptors is the **Constriction of vascular smooth muscles**. Alpha adrenergic receptors, particularly α1 receptors, are primarily responsible for the vasoconstriction effect in many vascular beds. When these receptors are stimulated by catecholamines (like epinephrine and norepinephrine), they lead to the contraction of smooth muscle cells in the walls of blood vessels.\r\n\r\nThis constriction of blood vessels results in increased peripheral vascular resistance, which can elevate blood pressure. The α1 receptors activate a Gq-protein-coupled mechanism, leading to increased intracellular calcium levels, which ultimately causes smooth muscle contraction.\r\n\r\nThe other actions listed, such as increasing the strength of vascular muscle contraction, blood flow to coronary arteries, heart rate, and velocity of conduction in the heart, are influenced by both alpha and beta receptors, but not exclusively by alpha receptors. For instance, beta receptors (β1 and β2) play significant roles in regulating heart rate, myocardial contractility, and the dilation of certain vascular beds, including coronary arteries.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 768.","responses":[{"text":"Constriction of vascular smooth muscles","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Strength of vascular muscle contraction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blood flow to coronary arteries","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Heart rate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Velocity of conduction in heart","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19223,"text":"Which of the following provides glucose to muscles during exercise?","explanation":"**Muscle glycogenolysis** is the primary and most immediate source of glucose for muscles during exercise.\r\n\r\nMuscles store glucose in the form of glycogen, which can be rapidly broken down into glucose-1-phosphate through a process called glycogenolysis. This process occurs within the muscle itself, allowing it to have quick access to a localized supply of glucose. Muscle glycogenolysis is particularly important during short bursts of intense activity or when immediate energy is needed.\r\n\r\nWhile muscle glycogenolysis is the primary source of glucose for muscles during exercise, it's important to note that other processes also contribute.\r\nThe liver stores glycogen and can release glucose into the bloodstream through hepatic glycogenolysis. This glucose can then be taken up by muscles for energy as needed. In cases where glycogen stores are depleted, the liver can synthesize glucose from non-carbohydrate precursors, a process known as gluconeogenesis. This newly synthesized glucose can be released into the bloodstream and transported to muscles for energy production.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 770.","responses":[{"text":"Protein breakdown","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatic gluconeogenesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lipolysis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Muscle glycogenolysis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatic glycogenolysis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19225,"text":"Which of the following is responsible for the down-regulation of a receptor in the presence of an excess of a hormone?","explanation":"When there is an excess of a hormone in the bloodstream and continuous binding of the hormone to its receptor on the cell membrane, the cell may become desensitized to the hormone's signal. To prevent overstimulation and maintain cellular responsiveness, the cell initiates a process called **internalization.** During internalization, the hormone-receptor complex is taken up into the cell via endocytosis, effectively removing the receptor from the cell membrane. This internalization reduces the number of available receptors on the cell surface, making the cell less responsive to the hormone's presence.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 921.","responses":[{"text":"Internalization of receptor","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Chemical nature of receptor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Activation of receptor molecule","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Synthesis of receptor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Binding of hormone to receptor","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19227,"text":"Which of the following increases the secretion of growth hormone from the anterior pituitary gland?","explanation":"When an individual engages in physical **exercise,** especially high-intensity or resistance training, it places a considerable physiological demand on the body. In response to this stress, the anterior pituitary gland increases the secretion of growth hormone. This hormone plays a crucial role in tissue growth and repair, making it essential during periods of increased physical activity.\r\n\r\nOn the contrary, several factors act to inhibit the secretion of growth hormone. Obesity is one such factor; excess adipose tissue can lead to elevated levels of somatostatin, a hormone that inhibits the release of growth hormone. Additionally, hyperglycemia, or high blood sugar levels, can also suppress growth hormone secretion.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 935.","responses":[{"text":"Exercise","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Free fatty acids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Somatostatin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperglycemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Obesity","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19228,"text":"Which of the following is the normal constituent of urine?","explanation":"**Urobilinogen** is one of the end products of heme metabolism, specifically the breakdown of bilirubin. Bilirubin is a yellow pigment that results from the breakdown of hemoglobin, the oxygen-carrying protein in red blood cells. When hemoglobin is broken down, biliverdin is initially formed, which is then converted into bilirubin. Bilirubin, in turn, undergoes further metabolic processes in the liver, resulting in the formation of urobilinogen.\r\n\r\nUrobilinogen is then released into the bloodstream and eventually excreted in the urine. Its presence in urine gives it a characteristic yellow color. The levels of urobilinogen in urine can vary depending on various factors, including the rate of red blood cell breakdown, liver function, and intestinal bacterial activity.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 875.","responses":[{"text":"Stercobilin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urobilinogen","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Biliverdin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bilirubin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19229,"text":"What does 'decreased glucose tolerance' mean?","explanation":"**Decreased glucose tolerance** refers to a condition where the body's ability to regulate blood glucose levels is impaired compared to the normal physiological response. \r\n\r\nSpecifically, decreased glucose tolerance means that the body has a reduced ability to clear glucose from the bloodstream after a meal or a glucose challenge. When an individual with decreased glucose tolerance consumes glucose-containing foods or undergoes a glucose tolerance test, their blood glucose levels tend to **rise to higher levels and take longer to return to normal** compared to someone with normal glucose tolerance.\r\n\r\nThis condition is a precursor to **impaired glucose tolerance (IGT)** and **type 2 diabetes**. It indicates that the individual is at an increased risk of developing diabetes because their body is struggling to handle glucose effectively.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 988.","responses":[{"text":"Decreased ability to absorb glucose from diet","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Following a glucose load, the body responds by hyperglycemia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Normal physiological response","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased ability to absorb glucose from diet","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Following a glucose load, the body responds by hypoglycemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19230,"text":"A 21-year-old girl visits the clinic complaining of drowsiness, weight gain, puffiness of the face, and menstrual irregularities. The doctor advises some blood tests and she is diagnosed with hypothyroidism. The doctor prescribes her thyroxin as a treatment. Through which of the following does thyroxin act?","explanation":"In the context of hypothyroidism, where there is an insufficient production of thyroid hormones, the treatment typically involves providing synthetic thyroxin (T4) to the patient, as mentioned in the case of the 21-year-old girl. Once administered, T4 is converted into the more active T3 within cells.\r\n\r\nThyroid hormones act by interacting with nuclear chromatin, specifically by binding to **thyroid hormone receptors (TRs) located in the nucleus** of target cells. This binding leads to the formation of hormone-receptor complexes that then interact with specific DNA sequences, called thyroid hormone response elements (TREs), within the genes' regulatory regions. This interaction with TREs promotes the transcription of genes involved in metabolic processes and cellular energy production.","reference":"1.Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 945","responses":[{"text":"Stimulation of enzyme synthesis at ribosome level","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cell surface receptor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nuclear receptor","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Direct activation at the enzyme level","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interaction with nuclear chromatin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19232,"text":"A 38-year-old male visits the clinic with complaints of weight gain and weakness of muscles. On examination, he has thin arms and legs, purplish bruises over the abdomen and hip region, and a round face. After performing some blood tests he is diagnosed with Cushing syndrome. Which of the following electrolytes would the report show to be increased in this patient?","explanation":"In terms of electrolyte imbalances associated with Cushing syndrome, the most relevant one is an increase in blood **sodium** (sodium ion or Na+) levels. This increase in sodium can result from the mineralocorticoid-like effects of excess cortisol. Cortisol, the primary glucocorticoid hormone, can stimulate the renal tubules to increase sodium reabsorption and potassium excretion, leading to sodium retention and potassium loss. This can subsequently result in hypernatremia (elevated sodium levels) and hypokalemia (decreased potassium levels).","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 956.","responses":[{"text":"Potassium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sodium","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Chloride","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Magnesium","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19235,"text":"Which of the following would NOT increase during starvation?","explanation":"During starvation, several physiological changes occur to maintain energy balance and sustain vital functions. One factor that does not increase during starvation is **glycogen.** Glycogen is a carbohydrate storage form found mainly in the liver and muscles. In the early stages of starvation, the body relies on glycogen stores to provide glucose for energy. However, as starvation continues, glycogen stores become depleted. The body breaks down glycogen into glucose to help maintain blood sugar levels. Once glycogen reserves are exhausted, the body turns to alternative sources of energy, such as fatty acids and ketone bodies.\r\n\r\nIn contrast, norepinephrine and epinephrine levels increase during starvation. These catecholamines are stress hormones that help mobilize energy reserves. They stimulate processes like lipolysis, which breaks down stored fats into fatty acids, and gluconeogenesis, the production of glucose from non-carbohydrate sources. These actions are essential for providing energy to the body when food intake is limited.\r\n\r\nKetone bodies, including acetoacetate, beta-hydroxybutyrate, and acetone, also increase during starvation. As glycogen stores deplete, the body begins to rely on fat metabolism to produce ketone bodies, which can serve as an alternative fuel source for various tissues, including the brain.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, glucagon levels rise during starvation. Glucagon acts in opposition to insulin and promotes glycogenolysis and gluconeogenesis to increase blood glucose levels when dietary glucose is scarce.","reference":"1.Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 858.","responses":[{"text":"Glucagon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glycogen","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Epinephrine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Norepinephrine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ketone bodies","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19238,"text":"Glucagon is a water-soluble hormone that binds to high-affinity receptors on cell membranes of hepatocytes. It activates a cascade of phosphorylation that leads to the formation of second messengers. Which of the following second messengers does glucagon lead to the formation of?","explanation":"**Glucagon** leads to the formation of **cyclic AMP (cAMP)** as the second messenger in its signaling cascade.\r\n\r\nWhen glucagon binds to its high-affinity receptors on the cell membranes of hepatocytes (liver cells), it initiates a series of intracellular events. One of the primary events is the activation of adenylate cyclase, an enzyme responsible for converting ATP (adenosine triphosphate) into cAMP. \r\n\r\nCyclic AMP then acts as a second messenger by activating protein kinase A (PKA), which in turn phosphorylates various target proteins within the cell. This phosphorylation cascade ultimately leads to the activation of enzymes involved in glucose production and release from the liver. Specifically, it promotes glycogenolysis (the breakdown of glycogen into glucose) and gluconeogenesis (the synthesis of glucose from non-carbohydrate precursors).","reference":"1.Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 846","responses":[{"text":"Cyclic GTP","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cyclic ATP","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cyclic AMP","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cyclic GDP","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cyclic ADP","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19241,"text":"Which of the following hormones has inhibitory effects on the release of secretin and cholecystokinin?","explanation":"**Somatostatin** is the hormone that has inhibitory effects on the release of secretin and cholecystokinin (CCK).\r\n\r\nSecretin and CCK are both hormones produced in the small intestine that play crucial roles in the digestive process. Secretin stimulates the pancreas to release bicarbonate-rich pancreatic juice into the duodenum to neutralize acidic chyme from the stomach. CCK, on the other hand, stimulates the release of digestive enzymes from the pancreas and the contraction of the gallbladder to release bile into the duodenum.","reference":"Costanzo L. Costanzo Physiology. 7th ed. Elsevier, Inc; 2021: 347.","responses":[{"text":"Glucagon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aldosterone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Insulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Growth hormone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Somatostatin","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":19246,"text":"A 40-year-old man comes into the outpatient department because of weight loss, increased appetite, and diplopia. On physical examination, his temperature is 37.7° C, pulse is 106/min, respiration rate is 15/min, and blood pressure is 140/80 mmHg. A fine tremor is observed in his outstretched hand. He has bilateral proptosis. The serum laboratory findings include a serum TSH level of 0.1 pU/mL. A radioiodine scan indicates increased diffuse uptake throughout the thyroid, Which of the following best describes the microscopic appearance of the patient's thyroid gland?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1081.","responses":[{"text":"Nodules with nests of cells separated by hyaline stroma that stains with Congo red","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Papillary projections in thyroid follicles and lymphoid aggregates in the stroma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Destruction of follicles, lymphoid aggregates, and Hurthle cell metaplasia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Follicular destruction with inflammatory infiltrates containing giant cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Enlarged thyroid follicles lined by flattened epithelial cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19247,"text":"A 30-year-old man visits the hospital because he has had a headache, weakness, and a 5-kg weight gain over the last 4 months. On physical examination, his face is puffy. His temperature is 36.9°C, pulse is 79/min, and blood pressure is 160/75 mm Hg while lying down. He has cutaneous striae over the lower abdomen and ecchymoses scattered over the extremities. A radiograph of the spine shows a compressed fracture of T11. Laboratory findings show a fasting plasma glucose level of 200 mg/dL, the plasma cortisol level is 38 pg/dL at 8:00 am and 37 pg/dL at 6:00 pm. Which of the following conditions is most likely to be present in this patient?","explanation":"The patient's presentation is consistent with **Cushing's syndrome**, a condition characterized by chronic exposure to excess glucocorticoids, primarily cortisol. \r\n\r\nThe clinical manifestations align with the metabolic and physiological changes associated with elevated cortisol levels. These include weight gain, facial puffiness, cutaneous striae (stretch marks), and ecchymoses (bruising). The laboratory findings of a high fasting plasma glucose level indicate impaired glucose metabolism, which is a common feature of Cushing's syndrome. Notably, the patient's cortisol levels remain consistently elevated throughout the day, which deviates from the normal diurnal cortisol rhythm. The presence of a compressed T11 fracture on the spine radiograph is likely due to the detrimental impact of excess cortisol on bone density, predisposing individuals to osteoporosis and fractures. \r\n\r\nGiven these clinical and biochemical features, the most likely cause of Cushing's syndrome in this patient is a **corticotroph adenoma of the anterior pituitary**, resulting in increased secretion of adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH). Elevated ACTH levels stimulate both adrenal glands, leading to **bilateral hyperplasia of the adrenal cortex,** a condition referred to as **Cushing's disease**, which accounts for the majority of endogenous Cushing's syndrome cases.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1071","responses":[{"text":"Adenoma of the right adrenal cortex without atrophy of contralateral adrenal cortex","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Corticotroph adenoma of the anterior pituitary, medullary carcinoma of thyroid, and bilateral nodular hyperplasia of the adrenal cortex","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Corticotroph adenoma of the anterior pituitary with bilateral hyperplasia of the adrenal cortex","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Small-cell carcinoma of the lung with bilateral hyperplasia of the adrenal cortex","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adenoma of the right adrenal cortex with atrophy of the contralateral adrenal cortex","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19249,"text":"A 52-year-old man has been concerned about a gradual weight gain for many years. He is 174cm (5 ft 7 inches) tall and weighs 91 kg (body mass index 30 kg/m^2). He is taking no medications. On physical examination, he has decreased sensation to pinprick and light touch over the lower extremities. Laboratory studies show glucose of 169 mg/dL, creatinine of 1.9 mg/dL, total cholesterol of 220 mg/dL, HDL cholesterol of 27 mg/dL, and triglycerides of 261 mg/dL. A chest radiograph shows mild cardiomegaly. Five years later, he has claudication in the lower extremities when he exercises. Based on these findings, which of the following complications in lower limbs can occur in this patient?","explanation":"Based on the described findings, the patient is at risk of developing **Gangrenous necrosis** in the lower limbs. The patient's clinical profile - obesity, impaired glucose tolerance (as indicated by a glucose level of 169 mg/dL), dyslipidemia (elevated total cholesterol and triglycerides, low HDL cholesterol), and renal impairment (creatinine of 1.9 mg/dL) - suggests metabolic syndrome and a high risk of atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease. The presence of claudication, which is pain in the limbs during exercise due to inadequate blood supply, further points towards peripheral arterial disease (PAD).\r\n\r\nPAD can lead to critical limb ischemia, where there is a severe reduction in blood flow to the lower extremities, increasing the risk of gangrenous necrosis. This condition is characterized by the death of tissue due to lack of blood supply, which can lead to gangrene if not promptly and adequately treated.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1071","responses":[{"text":"Gangrenous necrosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic pancreatitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Systemic amyloidosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ketoacidosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypoglycemic coma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19252,"text":"A 40-year-old man visits the physician due to weakness and easy fatiguability for 2 months. On physical examination, there are no remarkable findings. Laboratory studies show serum calcium of 11.5 mg/dl, inorganic phosphorus of 2.4 mg/dl, and parathyroid hormone of 54 pg/ml, which is near the top of the reference range. Radionuclear bone scan fails to show any uptake. What is the most likely cause of these findings?","explanation":"The patient's elevated serum calcium level, along with an inorganic phosphorus level at the lower end of the reference range and an elevated parathyroid hormone (PTH) level, suggests **primary hyperparathyroidism**. This condition is most commonly caused by a **parathyroid adenoma**, a benign tumor of the parathyroid gland.\r\n\r\nIn primary hyperparathyroidism, the parathyroid glands produce excessive amounts of PTH, which leads to increased calcium resorption from bone and decreased renal excretion of calcium. This results in elevated serum calcium levels, often causing symptoms like weakness and fatigue.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1093-1094.","responses":[{"text":"Parathyroid adenoma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic renal failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypervitaminosis D","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Parathyroid hyperplasia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Parathyroid carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19253,"text":"A 33-year-old, previously healthy woman dies suddenly after complaining of a mild sore throat the previous day, At autopsy, her adrenal glands are enlarged and there are extensive bilateral cortical hemorrhages. Which of the following organisms is responsible for the death of the patient?","explanation":"The patient's clinical presentation with adrenal gland enlargement and bilateral cortical hemorrhages suggests the possibility of **Waterhouse-Friderichsen syndrome**. This syndrome is most commonly caused by infection with **Neisseria meningitidis**, a gram-negative bacterium. \r\n\r\nWaterhouse-Friderichsen syndrome is characterized by massive adrenal hemorrhage due to the destruction of the adrenal glands by disseminated intravascular coagulation (DIC) triggered by the infection. Patients may present with sudden-onset shock, adrenal insufficiency, and often complain of a mild illness preceding the severe symptoms.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1122","responses":[{"text":"Cytomegalovirus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Histoplasma capsulatum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neisseria meningitidis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mycobacterium tuberculosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Streptococcus pneumonia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19255,"text":"A 45-year-old woman comes to the outpatient department with a feeling of fullness in her neck but has no past\r\ncomplaints. The enlargement has been gradual and painless for more than 1 year. Physical examination confirms diffuse enlargement of the thyroid gland without any apparent masses. Laboratory studies of thyroid function show a normal free T4 level and a slightly increased TSH level. What is the most likely cause of these findings?","explanation":"The most likely cause of diffuse thyroid enlargement with a slightly increased TSH level in this patient is **Hashimoto's thyroiditis**. \r\n\r\nHashimoto's thyroiditis is an autoimmune thyroid disorder characterized by the presence of autoantibodies against thyroid antigens, particularly thyroid peroxidase (TPO) and thyroglobulin. This autoimmune reaction leads to chronic inflammation of the thyroid gland, resulting in thyroid enlargement (goiter). The elevated TSH level is a compensatory response by the pituitary gland to try to stimulate the thyroid gland to produce more thyroid hormones.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1080","responses":[{"text":"Papillary carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diffuse nontoxic goiter","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Toxic multinodular goiter","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Subacute granulomatous thyroiditis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hashimoto's thyroiditis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":19257,"text":"A 32-year-old woman with systemic lupus erythematosus has been treated with corticosteroid therapy for several years, because of recurrent lupus nephritis. While on vacation, she undergoes an emergency appendectomy for acute appendicitis. On postoperative day 2, she becomes somnolent and develops severe nausea and vomiting. She then becomes hypotensive. Blood cultures are negative, and laboratory studies now show Na+ of 128 mmol/L, K+ of 4.9 mmol/L, Cl- of 89 mmol/L, CO2 of 19 mmol/L, glucose of 52 mg/dL, and creatinine of 1.3 mg/dL. Which of the following morphologic findings in the adrenal glands is most likely to be present in this patient?","explanation":"This patient, who has been on long-term corticosteroid therapy for lupus nephritis, is experiencing symptoms and laboratory findings suggestive of **adrenal insufficiency**. This condition can occur when exogenous corticosteroid treatment is abruptly discontinued or during periods of significant stress, such as surgery.\r\n\r\nThe most likely morphologic finding in the adrenal glands in this scenario is **bilateral cortical atrophy**. Prolonged administration of corticosteroids can suppress the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal (HPA) axis, leading to a reduction in endogenous cortisol production. In response to stress or the withdrawal of exogenous steroids, the adrenal glands may not be able to produce sufficient cortisol, resulting in adrenal insufficiency.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 116.","responses":[{"text":"Bilateral cortical atrophy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Bilateral cortical nodular hyperplasia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Solitary 1-cm adenoma without atrophy of the contralateral adrenal cortex","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bilateral hemorrhagic necrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bilateral caseating granulomas","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19258,"text":"A 25-year-old woman has noted breast secretions for the last 1 month. She is not breastfeeding and has never been pregnant. She has not menstruated for the past 5 months. Physical examination yields no abnormal findings. MRI of the brain shows a 0.7-cm mass in the adenohypophysis. Which of the following additional complications is most likely to be present in this patient?","explanation":"This patient presents with a combination of symptoms, including breast secretions, amenorrhea (absence of menstruation), and a small adenoma in the adenohypophysis (anterior pituitary gland). These findings are suggestive of a condition known as **prolactinoma**.\r\n\r\nProlactinomas are benign tumors of the pituitary gland that secrete excessive amounts of prolactin, a hormone responsible for stimulating breast milk production in females. However, in this case, the high levels of prolactin are causing **galactorrhea** (abnormal breast secretions) and suppressing gonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH) secretion from the hypothalamus. The reduced GnRH leads to decreased secretion of luteinizing hormone (LH) and follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) from the anterior pituitary, resulting in amenorrhea and infertility.\r\n\r\nTherefore, in addition to the breast secretions and amenorrhea, this patient is likely to have complications related to the hormonal imbalance caused by the prolactinoma. These complications include **infertility**, as the suppression of ovulation and menstruation can make it difficult for the patient to conceive.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1071.","responses":[{"text":"Infertility","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperthyroidism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acromegaly","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cushing's disease","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19259,"text":"A 23-year-old woman has a routine health status examination. Her body mass index is 22. Laboratory studies show fasting plasma glucose is 120 mg/dL. Urinalysis shows mild glucosuria, but no ketonuria or proteinuria. She has no detectable insulin autoantibodies. Her father was similarly affected at age 20. She is most likely to have a mutation in a gene encoding for which of the following?","explanation":"This patient's presentation, including a family history of similar symptoms and elevated fasting plasma glucose, is indicative of a condition known as **maturity-onset diabetes of the young (MODY)**. MODY is a rare form of diabetes that typically presents in young individuals and is often misdiagnosed as type 1 or type 2 diabetes.\r\n\r\nMODY is caused by mutations in various genes, and the specific gene involved can determine the clinical characteristics. In this case, the patient is most likely to have a mutation in the gene encoding for **glucokinase**.\r\n\r\n**Glucokinase** is an enzyme that plays a crucial role in glucose metabolism by facilitating the conversion of glucose to glucose-6-phosphate in the liver and pancreatic beta cells. Mutations in the glucokinase gene lead to a reduced sensitivity of pancreatic beta cells to glucose, resulting in a higher fasting plasma glucose level without significant ketonuria or proteinuria. This form of MODY is often referred to as MODY2.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1105.","responses":[{"text":"MHC DR","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucokinase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucagon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Insulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"GLUT4","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19260,"text":"A 42-year-old man sees his physician because he has had polyuria and polydipsia for the last 4 months. His medical history shows that he fell off a ladder and hit his head just before the onset of these problems. On physical examination, there are no specific findings. Laboratory findings include serum Na+, 155 mmol/L; K+, 3.9 mmol/L; Cl-, 111 mmol/L; C02,27 mmol/L; glucose 84 mg/dL; creatinine, 1 mg/dL; and osmolality, 350 mOsm/mL. The specific gravity of urine is 1.002. This patient is most likely to have a deficiency of which of the following hormones?","explanation":"The clinical presentation of polyuria (excessive urination) and polydipsia (excessive thirst) in this patient, along with the laboratory findings, strongly suggests a deficiency of **antidiuretic hormone (ADH)**, also known as vasopressin.\r\n\r\nADH is a hormone produced by the hypothalamus and released from the posterior pituitary gland. It plays a crucial role in regulating water balance in the body by increasing water reabsorption in the kidneys. When ADH is deficient or not functioning properly, as in this case, it leads to an inability to concentrate urine adequately, resulting in the excretion of large volumes of dilute urine (specific gravity of 1.002 in this case).\r\n\r\nThe head injury mentioned in the patient's medical history may have disrupted the production or release of ADH. This condition is known as **central diabetes insipidus**, where the body loses excess water due to the inability to reabsorb it in the renal tubules, leading to hypernatremia (elevated serum sodium levels) and the characteristic symptoms of excessive thirst and urination.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1073.","responses":[{"text":"Antidiuretic hormone","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Melatonin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Corticotrophin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prolactin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oxytocin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19261,"text":"A 51-year-old man has noted increasing weakness and weight gain over the past 5 months. He has experienced low back pain for the past week. On physical examination, vital signs include a temperature of 37.3°C, pulse of 80/min, respirations of 15/min, and blood pressure of 155/95 mm Hg. He has bilateral breast enlargement, testicular atrophy, and a prominent fat pad in the posterior neck and back. His serum ACTH level is low. A radiograph of the spine shows decreased bone density with a compression fracture at T9, Which of the following findings is most likely to be present in this patient?","explanation":"The clinical presentation described in this patient, including weakness, weight gain, low back pain, bilateral breast enlargement, testicular atrophy, and the presence of a prominent fat pad in the posterior neck and back, is highly suggestive of **Cushing's syndrome**. Cushing's syndrome results from chronic exposure to excessive levels of glucocorticoids, which can be endogenous or exogenous in origin.\r\n\r\nGiven the specific findings and the radiographic evidence of decreased bone density with a compression fracture at T9, it is likely that the underlying cause of Cushing's syndrome in this patient is **adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH)-independent**. This means that the excessive cortisol production is not being driven by an abnormality in the pituitary gland (such as a pituitary adenoma) or due to exogenous corticosteroid use.\r\n\r\nTherefore, the most likely finding in this patient would be a **left adrenal 10-cm solid mass**. This adrenal mass is likely responsible for the unregulated cortisol production, leading to the clinical manifestations of Cushing's syndrome, including the metabolic abnormalities and bone density loss seen in this case.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1117.","responses":[{"text":"Decreased radionuclide uptake in a thyroid gland nodule","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary 6-cm right hilar mass on chest radiograph","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left adrenal 10-cm solid mass with abdominal CT scan","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sella turcica enlargement with erosion on head CT scan","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Retroperitoneal 5-cm mass at the aortic bifurcation on pelvic MRI scan","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21165,"text":"Hypertriglyceridemia is associated with which of the following condition?","explanation":null,"reference":"https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6068776/#:~:text=Hypertriglyceridemia%20(HTG)%20is%20one%20of,to%2010%25%20of%20all%20cases.","responses":[{"text":"Diabetic foot","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diabetes type 1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Appendicitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pancreatitis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Retinopathy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21780,"text":"A 65-year-old woman came to the clinic. She has been on oral steroids for chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) and had a DEXA scan showing a T score of -1.8. Which of the following would be the best management?","explanation":null,"reference":"Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine, 24th Edition, page 1047-1049.","responses":[{"text":"Calcium and vitamin D supplements","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alendronate","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Abaloparatide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"All of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Raloxifene","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21869,"text":"Empagliflozin belongs to which class of drugs?","explanation":null,"reference":"Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine, 23rd edition, page 748.","responses":[{"text":"DPP 4 inhibitor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"GLP 1 agonist","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sodium-glucose co-transporter 2 inhibitor","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Biguanides","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sodium-glucose co-transporter 1 inhibitor","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21870,"text":"A patient presented in the emergency department (ER) with diabetic ketoacidosis. What is the immediate investigation performed for the management?","explanation":null,"reference":"Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine, 23rd edition, page 736.","responses":[{"text":"CBC","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"UCE","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arterial blood gases (ABGs)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"HbA1c","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Random blood sugar (RBS)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21959,"text":"A patient presented with weakness, lethargy, and significant weight loss of 5kg. His laboratory investigations revealed hypocalcemia and hyponatremia. What is the best investigation to reach the diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine, 24th edition, page 672.","responses":[{"text":"OGTT","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"TSH","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dexamethasone suppression test","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Synacthen test","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"PTH","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22003,"text":"A 30-year-old pregnant woman, who is a known case of Grave's disease and has been taking medications for it came for consultation regarding her treatment during pregnancy. Which of the following will be the drug of choice for this patient?","explanation":null,"reference":"Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine, 23rd edition, page 651.","responses":[{"text":"Carbimazole","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phenytoin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iodine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Beta blocker","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Propylthiouracil","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22004,"text":"What is the treatment for oligomenorrhea?","explanation":null,"reference":"Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine, 23rd edition, page 659.","responses":[{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metformin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"COCPs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cyproterone acetate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cyclical progesterone","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22122,"text":"A 30-year-old patient presents with complaints of 5 kg weight loss, fatigue, lethargy, polyuria, and polydipsia. His blood sugar level was raised. What is the best treatment for this patient?","explanation":null,"reference":"Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine, 23rd edition, page 746.","responses":[{"text":"Start insulin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"GLP-1 receptor agonists","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glyburide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thiazolidinediones","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metformin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22205,"text":"A young female presents to her gynecologist complaining of irregular menstrual periods, galactorrhea, and decreased libido. She also reports experiencing headaches and vision changes (visual field defects). Physical examination reveals no abnormalities. A blood test is performed and prolactin levels are 800 ng/mL. What is the best management for this patient?","explanation":null,"reference":"Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine, 23rd edition, page 685.","responses":[{"text":"Observation alone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transsphenoidal pituitary resection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucagon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Somatostatin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bromocriptine","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22206,"text":"What are the lab findings in hypopituitarism?","explanation":null,"reference":"Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine, 23rd edition, page 680.","responses":[{"text":"No change in prolactin levels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"High FSH and LH","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased ACTH","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Low FSH and LH","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Low FSH, high LH","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22207,"text":"A woman presented to the clinic with her husband with complaints of amenorrhea for 4 months. The couple has 2 kids and the husband has azoospermia. The woman has prolactin levels of 400 ng/ml. What will be the next best step?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 684.","responses":[{"text":"Repeat husband's semen analysis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"MRI abdomen and pelvis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"MRI pituitary","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pregnancy test","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ultrasound abdomen and pelvis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22240,"text":"A patient presented in the emergency department (ER) with Diabetic Ketoacidosis (DKA). His serum sodium levels were 106 mmol/L. Which of the following fluids would be administered?","explanation":null,"reference":"Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine, 23rd edition, page 737.","responses":[{"text":"3% saline","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"5% Dextrose","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypotonic saline","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Normal saline","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ringer's lactate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22242,"text":"A 60-year-old lady with NKCM presented in the outpatient department (OPD) with complaints of dyspnea and stridor. Examination revealed a large retrosternal goiter. Her thyroid profile was normal. Which of the following would be the best management?","explanation":null,"reference":"https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2752232/","responses":[{"text":"Radioactive iodine (RAI)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anti-thyroid drugs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Total thyroidectomy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Steroids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"B-blockers","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22409,"text":"In which of the following diseases the dose of levothyroxine is reduced?","explanation":null,"reference":"Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine, 24th edition, page number: 657-8.","responses":[{"text":"All of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neurological disorders","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ischemic heart diseases","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Respiratory disorders","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hematological disorders","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22413,"text":"Which of the following is true regarding De Quervain thyroiditis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine, 23rd edition, page 638, 646.","responses":[{"text":"It is painless","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased RAIU","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Anti-thyroid drugs are effective in treatment","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It follows bacterial infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased RAIU","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22415,"text":"A 60-year-old lady presented in the clinic with complaints of irritability and lethargy. Her lab values showed Ca=11.2 mg/dL, phosphate levels were low and ALP was raised.\r\nWhat is the best next step to reach the diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine, 23rd edition, page 663.","responses":[{"text":"PTH","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Bone X-ray","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"LFTs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"UCE","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"TSH","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22947,"text":"A 9-year-old girl is brought to the pediatrician due to concerns about her growth. Her parents report that she has consistently been below the 3rd percentile for height and they have noticed a lack of height gain compared to her classmates. Otherwise, she is good at studies. The girl's medical history is unremarkable and she has not experienced any significant illnesses. On examination, her growth velocity is significantly below the expected range for her age, and her bone age is delayed for his height age. What is the most likely cause of the patient's short stature?","explanation":null,"reference":"Khan PA. Basis of Pediatrics. 10th ed. Paramount Books (Pvt.) Ltd; 2018: 450.","responses":[{"text":"Growth hormone deficiency","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Familial short stature","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Constitutional delay","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Turner syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypothyroidism","correct":false,"visible":false}]}
]

